review_blob: Pours a deep mahogany with a lasting head. aroma is sweet and malty. flavor is aggressively roasty with strong cocoa and coffee notes. Not my favorite brown ale.
Pours a cloudy light copper. Aroma is fruity and hoppy. Flavor is dominated by hops. Quite bitter for a pilsner in my opinion. Good, but not what I expected from the style.

Copper colored with a small, short lived head. Aroma is dominated by wheat and malts. Somewhat lighter taste and mouthfeel than I expected but quite refreshing. Offers a good balance between the cascade hops and caramel malts. A little less carbonation would make this one much more appealing.
beer_name: Blue Moon Rounder Belgian Style Pale

review_blob: I could write about aroma, taste, appearance and overall impression as I usually do but this beer deserves more. I dont know how they did it but from first sip to last I was treated to a flashback to memories of warm banana bread at family meals and gatherings. Enjoying this beer was like taking a walk down memory lane to simple pleasures and comfort. Well done!

Pours clear gold with a short lived head. Aroma is a pleasant mix of spices and herbs. Flavor is smooth, effervescent, balanced and refreshing with very little aftertaste. A nice example of the style. Would pair well with a hearty meal including sausage and bacon.

Pours a sparkling light gold with a lasting head. Aroma is herbal with a hint of spice. Flavor is sweet up front and balanced in the finish. A little too sweet for my taste. Becomes somewhat cloying after a few sips.

Pours a deep brown with a short lived head. Aroma of roasted malts as expected. Flavor is well balanced, smooth and surprisingly refreshing for a brown ale. Nice hints of chocolate and toffee in the taste. One of my favorites from this brewer.
beer_name: Sierra Nevada Tumbler Autumn Brown Ale

review_blob: Pours light clear copper with a lasting thin head. Aroma is slight with hints of spice and citrus. Flavor is smooth but thin. I can taste the spices and fruits from the yeast but dont really pick up the toffee and caramel. A slightly acidic aftertaste hints that this would be a good beer to pair with sweet barbecue.
Pours medium copper with a thin lasting head. Very slight malt aroma. Flavor is well balanced with very little aftertaste. Somewhat tame but quite easy to drink.

Pours medium copper with a lasting white head. Aroma is citrus hops with a hint of spice. Flavor is aggressively hoppy but well rounded. Only a slight spicy bitterness in the aftertaste makes this a very refreshing beer that would be good for a session IPA.
Pours a hazy bright copper. Very little aroma. Flavor is quite bland with a hint of agave sweetness in the background and finish. Pales in comparison with their Belgian White.
Pours a deep ruby red with a lasting head. Aroma of roasted malt is faint. Flavor is well balanced and smooth. Notes of chocolate and dark fruit. An easy to drink porter but nothing to rave about.

Pours a medium copper gold with a very short lived head. Aroma is floral hops and spices. Taste is somewhat astringent and sharp. The hops dominate the flavor and add to the beers bitterness. Too much carbonation for my liking but still a good beer.

Pours a dark and slightly hazy ruby red with a decent head. Aroma of fruit and dark malt. Flavor is complex with hints of raisins and chocolate. Finish is slightly thin and short lived. The flavor becomes more complex and well rounded as the beer warms.

Pours a clear light gold with no head. Aroma is dominated by apples as expected. Flavor is sweet apple juice. Palate is smooth and somewhat creamy. Tastes like a mix of Miller Lite & apple juice. Strange but not terrible.

Pours a clear light copper with a short lived head. Corn aroma. Flavor is smooth and balanced but bland. An easy drinking BBQ beer for a hot summer day. The 5.5% alcohol is icing on the cake (no pun intended). My new go to macro.

Pours opaque black with a short lived head. Aroma is dominated by cocoa and sweet malt. Flavor is smooth and rich with chocolate and roasted malt being dominant. Very smooth and creamy mouthfeel. This certainly qualifies as a winter warmer.

Pours an almost opaque ruby red with a thin head. Aroma is subdued and slightly sweet. Flavor is hoppy up front with a strong sweet malt backbone. Mouthfeel is smooth and silky. Chocolate comes through in the aftertaste.
Pours a hazy golden copper with a short lived head. Aroma is sweetly floral. Well balanced flavor is a little watery and thin. Refreshing but not memorable.

Pours orange/mahogany with a lasting head. Slightly sweet aroma. Smooth, creamy and sweet. This is certainly a winter sipping ale and at 7% should warm up those winter chills. Very well balanced flavor with a rounded finish.

Pours cloudy orange/red with the largest fluffy white head of any beer I have ever poured out of a bottle. Not sure what that indicates about the beer but here goes.Tastes awful!!! Maybe I got a bad bottle. DRAIN POUR!
Looks great in the glass. Mahogany red with a thin but lasting head. Aroma of sweet caramel malts. Flavor is mild and somewhat watery with a creamy texture. Decent but not memorable.
Pours clear golden tan with a small lasting head. Very little aroma. Flavor is well balanced with a crisp, clean mouthfeel. This would be a great session ale for a hot summer day.

Pours an opaque black with a short lived off white head. Aroma is dominated by chocolate and roasted malts. I dont pick up very much banana in the flavor. Silky smooth on the tongue with a heavy dose of roasted malts.
beer_name: Thomas Creek Banana Split Chocolate Stout

review_blob: Pours a cloudy golden yellow with a fluffy head. Aroma is fruity and spicy with hints of banana and cloves. Flavor is light and refreshing and quite complex. This is one of the best beers I have tried recently. I would certainly recommend this to anyone who wants to try this style.
UPDATED: JUL 11, 2013

Pours a dark ruby red with no head. Slight malt sweetness in the aroma. Flavor is malty sweet with coffee and hints of chocolate. The roasting of the malts really shines through. Slightly hoppy and alcohol tinged finish. A nice sipping beer with a cool name.
Pours a medium mahogany with a short lived head. Aroma of piney hops. Flavor is dominated by hops with a hint of malt. Mouthfeel is quite dry and somewhat astringent with a lingering hop bitterness.
Pours a medium dark copper with a quickly diminishing head. Very little aroma. Flavor is well balanced but quite unassuming.
Pours a hazy reddish bronze with a lasting head. Malty aroma. Flavor is well balanced with up front malt sweetness and a citrusy hop finish. Low carbonation.
Pours a clear light bronze with a small, lasting head. Not much aroma. Texture is smooth but somewhat watery with no aftertaste. Flavor has hints of toasted malt. Not too bad for a macro beer.
Pours a clear gold with a surprisingly lasting head.Very little aroma. Flavor is quite thin and watery. Not offensive, just another macro thirst quencher.

Bottle. Pours a clear bright to medium copper with a nice lasting head. Aroma is grassy hops. Flavor is quite malty with hints of chocolate. Not what I was expecting from a pale ale. Drinkable but not really enjoyable.

Bottle. Pours a hazy, slightly cloudy medium copper with a lasting white head. Aroma is a mixture of citrus and floral hops. Flavor is packed with hops. Slightly astringent but not overly bitter. The citrus bite from the hops really comes through in each sip. A very nice example of the style. Would pair well with spicy Mexican or southwest dishes.

Rating #600: I had to pick a local brew for this milestone.

Can. Pours a clear copper bronze with a lasting head. Aroma is floral and soapy. Flavor is dominated by citrus hops with little balance from the malts. Somewhat astringent and metallic. Not one of my favorites.

Can. Pours clear golden brown with a lingering head. Aroma is dominated by citrus notes from the hops. Flavor is a bitter and astringent hop attack with little resistance from the malts. Somewhat difficult to drink due to the faint metallic and oily flavor of the hops. I may need to give this one another chance in the future.
beer_name: 21st Amendment Brew Free or Die IPA

review_blob: Can. Pours a clear golden brown with a lasting head. Aroma is quite bland. Flavor is a good balance between the hops and malts with the malts providing a sweetness in the finish. Very low carbonation. Overall a decent ESB but not one that I would seek out.

Bomber. Pours clear copper brown with a lingering white head. Very nice lacing. Aroma is a floral mixture of hops and fruit. The flavor is a perfect balance of floral and citrus hops with a nice backbone of malt. The alcohol bite is subtle and unassuming but no doubt in attendance. If this is an el dank mistake then lets toast to the hope that he makes many more. This would undoubtedly compliment a full platter of spicy nachos or hot wings. Bravo to the lads (and ladies) at Sweetwater.

Bottle. Pours a dark ruby red with a substantial lasting head. Aroma is sweet and malty. Flavor is well balanced between the toasted malts and the hops making this a very drinkable brown ale. Hopefully more brewers will experiment with this Citra hop. This beer would pair well with roasted chicken or beef.

Bottle. Pours a bright copper with a short lived head. Aroma is sweet with a hint of hops. Flavor is smooth and well balanced with a hint of hops throughout. The minimal carbonation makes this beer a pleasure to drink. Break out the shepherds pie or bangers and mash to go with this one.

Bottle: Pours honey brown with a short lived head. Aroma is slightly hoppy with a hint of chocolate. Flavor is slightly sweet with a backbone of hops. The rye comes through nicely with a hint of sweetness in the finish.

Bottle. Pours a medium brown with a nice head. Aroma is dominated by hops with a fruity character. Hop devil indeed. If you dont like hoppy beer then stay away from this one. Hops are dominant in the flavor as expected. Not overly bitter but still a face slap of resiny hoppiness. This would ruin your palate for any food except maybe the hottest chili or curry.

Bottle. Pours hazy golden copper with a lasting head. Aroma of citrus and wheat. Flavor is well balanced between the citrus flavored hops and the biscuit malts. Quite tasty and satisfying. Would pair well with nice yeasty bread and sharp cheese.

Bottle. Pours dark mahogany with very little head. Aroma is fruity with a hint of raisins. Flavor is a mix of fruity sweetness and a hard to define bitterness. Mouthfeel is thin but adequate. A metallic alcohol finish ruins the experience of this one. Would not recommend.
beer_name: Heavy Seas Mutiny Fleet Below Decks

review_blob: Bottle. Pours jet black with an off white head. Aroma is coffee and roasted malt. Silky smooth mouthfeel with a well balanced dark malt flavor from start to finish. Just the right amount of carbonation and alcohol.to make this a superb porter. Well done. Would pair well with a frozen desert or ice cream.

Can. Pours opaque black with a lasting head. Aroma is coffee roasted malt. Flavor  is dominated by roasted malt with a slight sweetness in the finish. Somewhat thin and watery mouthfeel make this a below average stout.

Can. (Caveat... I am not a fan of this beer style but it was part of a mix pack) Pours cloudy golden tan with a huge head which takes time to diminish. Aroma is sweet baby vomit and fresh baked bread. Flavor reminds me of a mimosa (champagne & orange juice) made with weak and watery orange juice. Not an awful beer but I would not buy it again.
Can. Pours an orange gold with a lasting white head. Aroma is dominated by citrus hops. Flavor is bitter from the hops and minimal malts. Rather hard to drink due to the bitterness and dryness.
Bottle. Pleasant hoppy aroma. Nicely balanced hop flavor from start to finish. Smooth and easy to drink makes this a good session APA.

Bomber. Pours copper gold with a lasting head. Aroma is dominated by hops as expected. Nice balanced flavor with aggressive hoppiness that does not overwhelm the palate. Finishes bitter but not unpleasant. Overall a nice example of the style. Would pair well with spicy curry or chili.
beer_name: Spanish Peaks Chugs Private Stash Big Bite IPA
